<body id="mainbackgrounddesign">
    <%- include ('partials/navbar.ejs') %>
    <div class="container mt-5">
        <div class="text-center mb-4">
            <h2 id="ds1">UI/UX Design</h2>
            <p id="ds1">Below are some of my works. Click on each to explore more about them!</p>
        </div>

        <!-- GA -->
        <div class="row mb-5">
            <div class="col-md-6">
                <!-- Clickable Image that triggers the modal -->
                <a href="#" data-bs-toggle="modal" data-bs-target="#project1Modal">
                    <img src="UIUX6.PNG" class="img-fluid" alt="Project 1">
                </a>
            </div>
            <div class="col-md-6 d-flex flex-column justify-content-center">
                <h3 id="ds2">Design GA</h3>
                <p id="ds2">
                This is my UI/UX Design GA. My business name is Harutobi and the logo I'm using is 
                the same as the design logo I used for my C257 Fundamentals Of Design GA. The app, 
                Harutobi, is a one - stop travel app with information from Changi Airpot App, 
                Krisflyer App, and the relevant Travel Agencies App all in one. 
                </p>

                <p>
                The purpose of having this app is to make sure all important information regarding 
                travelling are inside, so that it makes it more convenient for users. There is user 
                persona, user flow, sitemap and my Harutobi 5 pages Low-Fidelity Wireframe. 
                </p>

                <p>
                The Harutobi 5 pages Low - Fidelity wifreframe is a visualization of how the actual app 
                would look like. I use a bit of personal and fictional information for my user persona to 
                make it more interesting. 
                </p>

                <p>
                Regarding the sitemap, it is actually very detailed and specific, it has information of 
                everything travel related inside. The user flow is similar to the sitemap as it shows the 
                organization of the apps, what can the user(s) do to achieve their goal, so it's very 
                systematic in a way.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>

